Chapter One
Cologne
It was 4:30 in the morning in Italy. Cologne didn't like waking up so early. It was mainly because he had to be responsible for waking up the rest of the squad. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat gear, fastened his assault vest, and packed his belongings from the storage cabinet. He carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a breathing apparatus, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots making creaking noises on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think very hard just to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm, as it only rang half the time, and the speaker could only be heard as a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Cologne turned around and saw Captain Nemetschek approaching.
"Yes," Cologne answered.
"What method are you planning to use this time?"
Before Cologne could answer, the door opened, and Harris, Kress, and several others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Kress said.
"What woke you up?" Cologne asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use to wake everyone up today. Second, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," a soldier named Lavik replied. "You know how terrible the breakfasts are."
Cologne said, "You're right, Corporal Lavik." He reached out and pressed the switch. An ear-splitting alarm immediately sounded throughout the barracks. He heard shouting and a rush of hurried footsteps inside.
"Good grief, Varturi," Nemetschek said. "I thought they should have learned to get up with you by now."
"I've got my brothers from the new recruit training camp to thank for that," Cologne said, pointing at Harris, Kress, and Lavik. "But to be honest, their squad leader and platoon commander knew to get up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the squad ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked drowsy, while others seemed very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Cologne said cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, why do you have to wake us up that way?" asked a squad member (corporal).
"Cause the ordinary alarm clocks are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in." Cologne said.
"Bring your personal belongings," Cologne continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the squad, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Boldin Xiao in supervising and leading the squad. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your men have 15 minutes for a final check and to bring today's rations."
Members of the Exodus squad dispersed quickly. They were part of the Second Assault Regiment of the Second Group Army. Before the merger, they had been two independent squads, Cohort and Dagger. It was an elite squad, and Cologne felt a complex mix of emotions about being promoted to lieutenant, for many reasons.
Cologne and the first squad leader Nimich walked side by side along the well-lit road of the base, with lights on both sides powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun to adopt the "wild boar" tactic both in the air and on the ground.
"Another day, a new mission for the Hell's Vanguard," Nimich dryly remarked. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Ianlos City's outer frontline base. We've been sent to support the ground assault," Cologne said, taking a drag of his cigarette. He slightly blamed Kress for getting him hooked on smoking, but thinking back on the past year and the countless battles they had gone through, he let it go, saying nothing.
"Bad luck. The front lines are really tough," Nimich muttered. "All the messages coming from here are about 'supporting the war, aiding the Kurgan front,' why not support the Hauran front as well?"
"Good talk, brother," Cologne said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll go with the First Armor Platoon; no need to walk. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Did Captain Xiao send us a ride?" Nimich asked, surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not讨厌 either."
Cologne raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against the microphone on his throat, and moved his pack onto his back. "All units of Exodus Squad, assemble at the West Area Vehicle Yard after completing your tasks. We will depart with the First Armor Platoon at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Kress, and Lavik were all lower-ranking non-commissioned officers. Since basic training on Earth, the four of them had been good friends. Cologne felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since a week ago, when the previous platoon leader was shot by Daybreak snipers and had to retire due to injuries, Kress had taken over command of the second squad.
When they arrived at the vehicle yard, Cologne and Nimich's eyes fell upon approximately eight Kratos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were all in working order. Cologne quickly spotted Captain Boldin Xiao in the crowd, who was talking with the commander of the armor platoon. As they approached, Xiao looked at them and came forward, his usual impassive face showing no emotion.
"Corporal Nimich... Lieutenant Valduri..." he said, and Cologne slowed his pace. Captain Xiao looked at Cologne's holstered pistol, then raised his head. "Has the squad already been prepared?"
